    "summary": "Pompey the Great (Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus, 106–48 BC) was Rome's most celebrated general in the generation before Julius Caesar — a military prodigy who earned his cognomen 'Magnus' (the Great) from Sulla while barely in his twenties. His extraordinary career included the suppression of the Marian faction in Africa and Sicily, the defeat of Sertorius in Spain, the final destruction of Spartacus's slave army (claiming credit from Crassus), and the systematic elimination of Mediterranean piracy in just three months (67 BC).\n\nHis eastern campaigns (66–62 BC) were his greatest triumph: he defeated Mithridates VI of Pontus, reorganized the eastern Mediterranean into Roman provinces, and marched into Jerusalem, entering the Holy of Holies of the Second Temple. He returned to Rome with unprecedented prestige and wealth, but the Senate's refusal to ratify his eastern settlements and provide land for his veterans pushed him into the First Triumvirate with Caesar and Crassus. His rivalry with Caesar led to civil war; defeated at Pharsalus (48 BC), he fled to Egypt where he was assassinated on the beach by agents of Ptolemy XIII — a humiliating end for Rome's greatest living general.",
